ig</i> ‘stony, rocky’ + <i>denn</i>; Standen in Hawkinge (Kent) derives from Old English <i>stān</i> + <i>denn</i>; the Berkshire, Devon, Hertfordshire, Isle of Wight, and Staffordshire placenames derive from Old English <i>stān</i> + <i>dūn</i> ‘hill’."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"De","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Bright’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs Robert De Standon was born about 1314, in England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 son with Robert de Standon."},"et":{"about 1314–Deceased":"umbes 1314–Surnud","1310–1336":"1310–1336","1337–Male":"1337–Surnud","1314–Female":"1314–Surnud","1337":"1337","1314":"1314","1336":"1336","about 1314":"umbes 1314","1310":"1310","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1314–Deceased":"noin 1314–Kuollut","1310–1336":"1310–1336","1337–Male":"1337–Kuollut","1314–Female":"1314–Kuollut","1337":"1337","1314":"1314","1336":"1336","about 